<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Normal Distribution</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/Statistics/NormalDistrib=
ution.nb" download=3D"NormalDistribution.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/images/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=
=3D"27" alt=3D"DOWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download
 <span class=3D"display-i display-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</spa=
n></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"521.389" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/NormalDistribution_800.svg" class=
=3D" wolfram-c2c-wrapper mathworld-c2c_above" alt=3D"NormalDistribution" da=
ta-c2c-file=3D"/mathcode/NormalDistribution.txt" data-c2c-type=3D"text/html=
" id=3D"mathworld-c2c_above-0">
</div>
<p>
A normal distribution in a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Variate=
.html">variate</a> <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equatio=
ns/NormalDistribution/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-hei=
ght:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" alt=3D"X">=
 with <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Mean.html">mean</a> <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/NormalDistribution/Inlin=
e2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" width=3D"10" height=3D"21" alt=3D"mu"> and <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/Variance.html">variance</a> <img src=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/images/equations/NormalDistribution/Inline3.svg" class=3D"in=
lineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D=
"19" height=3D"21" alt=3D"sigma^2"> is a statistic distribution with <a hre=
f=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ProbabilityDensityFunction.html">probabi=
lity
 density function</a>
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0" style=3D"padding-left: 50px">
<tbody><tr><td align=3D"left"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/NormalDistribution/NumberedEquation1.svg" class=3D"numberedeq=
uation" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"195"=
 height=3D"46" alt=3D" P(x)=3D1/(sigmasqrt(2pi))e^(-(x-mu)^2/(2sigma^2)) ">=
</td><td align=3D"right" width=3D"3">
<div id=3D"eqn1" class=3D"eqnum">
(1)
</div>
</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<p>
on the domain <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/No=
rmalDistribution/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:1=
00%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"90" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x in (-i=
nfty,infty)">.
 While statisticians and mathematicians uniformly use the term "normal dist=
ribution"
 for this distribution, physicists sometimes call it a Gaussian distributio=
n and,
 because of its curved flaring shape, social scientists refer to it as the =
"bell
 curve." Feller (1968) uses the symbol <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/images/equations/NormalDistribution/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformu=
la" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"33" heig=
ht=3D"21" alt=3D"phi(x)"> for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/NormalDistribution/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"35" height=3D"21"=
 alt=3D"P(x)"> in the above equation, but then switches to <img src=3D"http=
s://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/NormalDistribution/Inline7.svg" =
class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"=
0" width=3D"32" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n(x)"> in Feller (1971).
</p>
<p>
de Moivre developed the normal distribution as an approximation to the <a h=
ref=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BinomialDistribution.html">binomial di=
stribution</a>, and it was subsequently used by Laplace in 1783 to study me=
asurement
 errors and by Gauss in 1809 in the analysis of astronomical data (Havil 20=
03, p.&nbsp;157).
</p>
<p>
The normal distribution is implemented in the <a href=3D"http://www.wolfram=
.com/language/">Wolfram Language</a> as <tt><a href=3D"http://reference.wol=
fram.com/language/ref/NormalDistribution.html">NormalDistribution</a></tt>[=
<i>mu</i>,
 <i>sigma</i>].
</p>
<p>
The so-called "<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/StandardNormalDistr=
ibution.html">standard normal distribution</a>" is given by taking <img src=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/NormalDistribution/Inlin=
